posts.name: Kade Dressing
posts.cooked:
After this season, my team and I were completely dissatisfied with our wiring and aim to enhance it for future competitions. Additionally, we wish to learn how others manage wire routing and design wiring that remains both aesthetically pleasing and functional.

Our current wiring setup involves using heat shrink tubing to connect wires and prevent tangling during operation. However, encountering CAN modules proved time-consuming due to the necessity of cutting into them for access. Furthermore, some wires became tangled, necessitating frequent connections using WAGO or similar connectors since we lacked sufficient long rolls of wire—plans to obtain longer rolls are in place.

Exploring alternatives such as nylon wraps and experimenting with different wire types has been initiated. This exploration stems from concerns raised during the Belton competition when an inspector mentioned outdated wire types that are more challenging to work with compared to newer options available to other teams.

If anyone has suggestions regarding wire types or can clarify what kind of wire was referenced, we would greatly appreciate the information.

posts.name: Jared Van Horn
posts.cooked: We used heat shrink to keep moving wires hooked together to prevent wire entanglement in our chains, but whenever we encountered a CAN issue, accessing it required cutting into it, which was extremely time-consuming. Split loom sleeving is fantastic for this—it’s been an absolute game-changer for our team this season!

We used heavily on our robot this year with a very important cable sleeving. We found that a specific brand works great for our smaller wires, like the CAN network and 18AWG power. We've switched to soldering everything this year, and it's made our CAN runs much easier. We also love Anderson Powerpoles and use zipties to keep things secure. For cable management, we use zipties to bundle wires together and strain relieve them to prevent unplugging. For example, we zip tie all our cable runs to keep them organized and stable.

posts.name: Nick Foote
posts.cooked:
The assistant has successfully cleaned up the text while preserving its original meaning. Here is the revised version without unnecessary elements:

We had to continuously use multiple sections of wire because we didn't have long rolls. Everyone’s focusing on the split loom nylon protectors is absolutely the right move, but this is definitely your biggest issue. You’ve taken a wire that should have only two points of failure (at either end) and added several more in between. That’s why you had to cut your heat shrink repeatedly to access each individual section. 

We experienced this problem in 2023 when we weren’t motivated enough to wire things correctly, which led to significant costs at every regional, travel, and competition. Given how expensive these events are, each incident was a waste of money. We should have just purchased longer CAN wires. After completely overhauling our wiring and connectors, we’ve never had a wiring issue since. I’m not a big fan of soldering, but if you’re new to it, a bad solder can cause problems down the line—it’s like a time bomb ready to go off.

posts.name: Kade Dressing
posts.cooked: We encountered several problems during the competition, including difficulties with soldering and insufficient wire due to past members' lack of knowledge and poor resource management. Our build team relied on outdated templates and subpar materials, which hindered our performance. This year, I took on a more active role as the programming lead, teaching others and managing resources despite the district's slow approval process. We struggled to obtain necessary parts quickly, leading to delays in upgrading our equipment. Additionally, our reliance on outdated robots further complicated matters. To address these issues, I plan to implement stricter standards for wiring and organization, ensuring safer and more efficient practices moving forward.

posts.name: Nick Foote
posts.cooked:
I’m sorry to hear you’ve been through so much trouble. Purchasing is definitely one of the most painful processes any team or individual at a company goes through. For many years, I’ve just been buying things for the team and not getting reimbursed because I considered it less of a burden to bear the cost myself. However, this year I bought some items for the team that were expensive enough that it became worth it to have them reimbursed. But it was a real drag when you had to involve a school foundation and ASB.

For your team, buying a spool of nice wire costing between $50 and $100 makes sense because a single match can cost over $400 to compete in, and if the wire fails during a match, it’s a waste of that money. It can be challenging to explain this to a school finance admin, especially when purchases take too long. That’s why purchasing as much as possible in the fall is crucial. Regardless of the game, you’ll need CAN wire. 

I hope you luck out with acquiring some new wires and electronics. 

As for the driver station, here’s a hint: ask a sponsor if they have any leftover laptops that aren’t Windows 11 compatible, and keep them hidden to avoid them being locked down.

posts.name: Dave Morrison
posts.cooked: What problems did you have with your CAN+ wago? We did that last year and had no failures. Note we used appropriate gauge ferrules, which is important due to the small wire (22ga). Wire needs to be strain relieved. Of course, it still has to be done correctly—a common initial error was forgetting to have the wire extend fully to the end of the ferrule. This year we switched to Molex-SL, which requires more work and skill initially but results in a smaller, faster, and easier-to-connect connector.

posts.name: Olivia
posts.cooked: Selecting the right type of zip ties is essential when connecting your power pole connectors. While the clips work well, our available zipties are too large to fit through the connector openings.

posts.name: bgg
posts.cooked: We used solder seal wire connectors for the first time this year and they will be on our robots in the future. They were mostly used for making short CAN branches for each motor controller as a precaution so the whole bus would still work if something went wrong in one. I think we had zero CAN issues over 3 events. I also recommend upgrading to Thrifty Nova CAN cables as a replacement if you are using SPARK MAX. The robot had hot glue on every connector that plugs in (no worries–it comes off easily with alcohol).

posts.name: Jai Gupta
posts.cooked: We love using adhesive cable tie mounts, McMaster slit corrugated tubing, and braided sleeving. We also plan wire routing during the design process to ensure our designs are electrically friendly and incorporate cable tie mounts into 3D printed parts. This allows us to be really efficient when wiring and have a step-by-step plan with prepped (one end crimped, one end uncrimped with slack) wires.

posts.cooked: I am a big fan of Anderson Powerpoles, particularly when zipped together with a ziptie to create a bulletproof connection. Additionally, I love the Powerpole Pins from the Powerpole product line—they make swapping connectors faster and provide more strength than a small ziptie alone.

posts.cooked:
We also need a new computer but the district won’t let us get one unless they put administrative protection on it removing our access to use driver station and stuff so we can’t get a new computer so we had to use mine instead.

If you really need to maybe you can ask your tech department to allow you to connect on certain ports and IP’s and give admin access on the driver station to be clear you would do this for at home development at comp you should use a laptop with full admin access.

An example the tech team could be allowing access to 10.TE.AM.* range of IP’s your typical IP address range used for the RoboRIO Radio and most co-processors 172.22.11.2 RoboRIO USB IP and also allow the ports as outlined in the game manual at https://frctools.com/2025/rule/R704 and port 22 for SSH access. But obviously this is an unideal setup but if it means that you can use a more powerful laptop for development and a comp laptop it could be a solution.

What kind of zip ties do you use to zip tie your powerpole connectors together? We just use small zip ties that fit in the hole, but wrapping it around also works. As long as you just have zipties you should be fine.
